Task 1: Data Understanding¶

1.1 Task Definition¶

  1. Objective:
  • This project aims to build a binary classification model using the Diabetes Prediction Dataset to predict whether an individual has diabetes.
  1. Reason:

  • Diabetes is a chronic condition where early detection is crucial, as it allows patients to intervene sooner, prevent complications, and reduce healthcare burdens.

  • Developing an effective prediction model can significantly support doctors in their diagnostic decisions.

  • Data Source: Kaggle - Diabetes Prediction Dataset

  • Dataset Overview: This dataset comprises around 100,000 health records, including features such as age, gender, smoking history, BMI, and blood sugar levels. The target variable is diabetes, where 0 indicates no diabetes and 1 indicates the presence of diabetes.

Task 2: Data Preparation & Modeling¶

2.1 Data Splitting¶

In this project, the dataset is split into 70% training, 15% validation, and 15% testing sets.

Reasons:

  • With a sufficiently large dataset, allocating 70% for training ensures the model has ample data to learn from.

  • The 15% validation set is used for tuning and selecting the best model.

  • The remaining 15% testing set provides an unbiased evaluation of the model’s final performance, helping to prevent data leakage.

  • Since the data does not involve any time series features, a random split is appropriate and justified.

In [791]:
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

train_val_df, test_df = train_test_split(data, test_size=0.15, random_state=42, stratify=data['diabetes'])

# Then, split the remaining 85% into training and validation sets

2.2 Preprocessing and Feature Engineering¶

2.2.1 Handling outliers and missing values¶

  1. Outliers

During data exploration and outlier analysis in Task 1, we found some outliers in the age and bmi features.

  • The age values range from 0 to 100. Although there are some extreme values, they still fall within a reasonable human age range.

  • The BMI values show some unusually high or low readings, but medically these should be retained to allow the model to recognise conditions such as obesity or underweight.

Therefore, no outlier removal is performed on age and bmi in order to preserve potentially valuable medical information.

  1. Missing values
In [793]:
unknown_count = (df['smoking_history'] == 'No Info').sum()
print(f"Number of 'No Info': {unknown_count}")

Number of 'No Info': 32881

When recoding the smoking_history feature, it was found that the original data contains a substantial proportion of the “No Info” category, amounting to 32,881 records.

2.2.2 Feature Transformation and Encoding¶

  • Numerical features are standardised, because models like KNN and SVM are sensitive to feature scales.

  • Categorical features are encoded using one-hot encoding to avoid implying any ordinal relationship between categories.

In [794]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

numeric_cols = ['age', 'bmi', 'HbA1c_level', 'blood_glucose_level']
categorical_cols = ['gender', 'hypertension', 'heart_disease', 'smoking_history']

def recategorize_smoking(smoking_status):
    if smoking_status == 'never':
        return 'non_smoker'
    elif smoking_status == 'current':
        return 'current_smoker'
    elif smoking_status in ['ever', 'former', 'not current']:
        return 'past_smoker'
    else:
        return 'unknown'

for df_ in [train_df, val_df, test_df]:
    df_['smoking_history'] = df_['smoking_history'].apply(recategorize_smoking)

To retain the substantial proportion of the “No Info” category, I grouped all uncovered or missing cases into a single “unknown” category. This grouping retains the completeness of the dataset and allows the model to learn from these ‘unknown’ cases explicitly. By simplifying the smoking_history feature from multiple categories down to just four — non_smoker, current_smoker, past_smoker, and unknown — the data becomes more manageable for subsequent analysis and modelling.

In [795]:
# Standardise the numerical features
scaler = StandardScaler()
train_df[numeric_cols] = scaler.fit_transform(train_df[numeric_cols])
val_df[numeric_cols] = scaler.transform(val_df[numeric_cols])
test_df[numeric_cols] = scaler.transform(test_df[numeric_cols])

By standardising the numerical features—age, BMI, HbA1c level, and blood glucose level—we ensure consistent data distribution, which facilitates more effective training of machine learning models.

In [796]:
# One-hot encode categorical variables
train_df = pd.get_dummies(train_df, columns=categorical_cols, drop_first=True)
val_df = pd.get_dummies(val_df, columns=categorical_cols, drop_first=True)
test_df = pd.get_dummies(test_df, columns=categorical_cols, drop_first=True)

# Ensure that the validation and test sets have the same columns as the training set
val_df = val_df.reindex(columns=train_df.columns, fill_value=0)
test_df = test_df.reindex(columns=train_df.columns, fill_value=0)

Perform one-hot encoding on the categorical variables to convert them into numerical format suitable for machine learning models. At the same time, ensure that the training, validation, and test sets share the same feature columns to avoid errors caused by differences in categories.

2.2.3 Feature Selection¶

This dataset contains a total of nine columns, including the target variable, which means the number of features is relatively small. Considering that each feature may hold useful information, no feature selection has been performed at this stage. During model training, Random Forest and XGBoost are capable of automatically assessing feature importance, which can further enhance model performance.

2.3 Model Training¶

2.3.1 Algorithm Choice¶

Selected Models:

  • Logistic Regression: Serves as a strong baseline model. It is straightforward, interpretable, and provides quick initial insights.

  • Decision Tree: Capable of capturing non-linear relationships. Easy to visualise and interpret, making it suitable for understanding feature importance.

  • Random Forest: An ensemble method that improves generalisation and performs well with mixed types of features. Robust to overfitting.

  • LinearSVC: Compared to the standard SVM, LinearSVC uses a linear kernel, making it computationally efficient—particularly advantageous for large-scale datasets.

  • K-Nearest Neighbours (KNN): A simple instance-based learning algorithm. Relies heavily on numerical features and is useful for understanding local decision boundaries.

  • XGBoost: A powerful gradient boosting framework known for its high performance, regularisation capabilities, and ability to handle imbalanced datasets effectively.

This diverse model selection helps compare both simple and complex algorithms and identify the most suitable one for our dataset.

# 1. Logistic Regression
lr = LogisticRegression(C=0.1, max_iter=1000, class_weight='balanced', random_state=42)

# Evaluate model performance on the original (non-resampled) training set

print(f"Val Accuracy: {val_accuracy:.3f}")

Logistic Regression Performance:
Train Accuracy: 0.887
Val Accuracy: 0.892

Logistic Regression Hyperparameter Settings:

  • C=0.1: A smaller value indicates stronger regularisation, which helps to prevent overfitting. It is particularly suitable for datasets with a large number of samples and a moderate number of features.

  • max_iter=1000: Sets the maximum number of iterations for the solver. A higher value ensures that the optimisation process converges fully and the model has sufficient time to train properly.

  • class_weight='balanced': Automatically adjusts the weights of each class to address class imbalance. This encourages the model to pay more attention to the minority class, helping to improve recall.

  • random_state=42: Fixes the random seed to ensure the experiment is reproducible.

Summary:

  • The accuracy score indicates that the Logistic Regression model generalizes well to unseen data, with no clear signs of overfitting or underfitting.

Task 3: Evaluation¶

3.1 Select Evaluation Metrics:¶

Task Type: Binary Classification (Diabetes Prediction)

  • Primary Metric: F1-score

  • Other Metrics: Precision, Recall, ROC-AUC

Reasons:

  • Since the dataset is imbalanced (only about 8.8% positive diabetes cases), accuracy alone is not a reliable metric.

  • The F1-score provides a balanced measure between precision and recall, making it well-suited for imbalanced classification.

  • ROC-AUC is widely used in medical diagnostics to evaluate the model’s ability to distinguish between positive and negative cases.

Ideal Metric Values:

Metric Ideal Range Explanation
Precision 0.75 – 0.90 Controls false positives while maintaining strong positive identification ability
Recall 0.75 – 1.00 Maximizes detection of diabetic patients, minimizing missed cases (false negatives)
F1-score 0.75 – 0.90 Balances precision and recall effectively
ROC-AUC ≥ 0.90 Indicates excellent class discrimination

Given the focus on early screening, recall is prioritized to reduce missed diagnoses. During later diagnostic stages, precision and overall accuracy become more important to reduce false alarms.

from sklearn.metrics import f1_score, precision_score, recall_score, roc_auc_score

from sklearn.metrics import f1_score, precision_score, recall_score, roc_auc_score
from sklearn.preprocessing import MinMaxScaler
import numpy as np

def evaluate_model(name, model, X_train, y_train, X_val, y_val):
    # Predict labels for training and validation sets
    y_train_pred = model.predict(X_train)
    y_val_pred = model.predict(X_val)

    auc = "N/A"  # Default value if ROC-AUC cannot be calculated

    try:
        # Try to get predicted probabilities for validation set
        y_val_proba = model.predict_proba(X_val)[:, 1]
        auc = roc_auc_score(y_val, y_val_proba)
    except AttributeError:
        try:
            y_val_scores = model.decision_function(X_val)


            if len(np.unique(y_val_scores)) > 2:
                scaler = MinMaxScaler()
                y_val_proba = scaler.fit_transform(y_val_scores.reshape(-1, 1)).flatten()
                auc = roc_auc_score(y_val, y_val_proba)
        except AttributeError:
            # If neither method is available, skip ROC-AUC calculation
            pass

    # Print evaluation metrics for training and validation sets
    print(f"\n{name} Performance:")
    print(f"  Train F1: {f1_score(y_train, y_train_pred):.3f}")
    print(f"  Val F1: {f1_score(y_val, y_val_pred):.3f}")
    print(f"  Train Precision: {precision_score(y_train, y_train_pred):.3f}")
    print(f"  Val Precision: {precision_score(y_val, y_val_pred):.3f}")
    print(f"  Train Recall: {recall_score(y_train, y_train_pred):.3f}")
    print(f"  Val Recall: {recall_score(y_val, y_val_pred):.3f}")
    print(f"  Val ROC-AUC: {auc}")

# Identify false negatives: cases where the true label is positive (1) but predicted as negative (0)
false_negatives = X_val_df[(X_val_df['True'] == 1) & (X_val_df['Pred'] == 0)]

Analysis of false positives:

  • High HbA1c levels may be mistakenly interpreted as indicators of diabetes even when the individual does not actually have the disease. Older age can introduce noise, as the model might overly rely on age and HbA1c while overlooking other features. In an effort to maximise recall, the model can become somewhat "conservative"—when faced with multiple high-risk factors, it tends to predict a positive result even if current blood glucose levels are not elevated, leading to false positives. This is likely because the model interprets the combined effect of these risk factors as a strong signal for diabetes, although these individuals might actually have metabolic syndrome or other chronic conditions without meeting the criteria for a diabetes diagnosis.

From several false negative samples, we can observe the following:

  • These individuals truly have diabetes, but their combination of risk factors may be less typical or less severe. For example, the patient at index 52890 is older but has relatively normal or low BMI, HbA1c, and blood glucose levels, and no hypertension or heart disease. The model likely relies heavily on these core metabolic indicators for prediction, so it fails to identify such cases.

  • Another possibility is that these patients might be in the early stages of diabetes or have their condition well-controlled, resulting in key biochemical markers (like HbA1c and blood glucose) not yet reaching the high-risk thresholds learned by the model.

  • A single high-risk factor might be overshadowed by other healthy features. For instance, the patient at index 53877 has elevated blood glucose, but their youth and low BMI may carry more weight in the model's assessment, leading it to underestimate the overall risk.

Summary:

These examples show that the XGBoost model struggles with individuals who fall into the grey area near the decision boundary.

Confusing cases include:

  • False positives: people without diabetes but with many diabetes risk factors, who look similar to real diabetes patients.

  • False negatives: people with diabetes whose key metabolic signs or related conditions are not typical or obvious, making them look like healthy individuals.

The main reason is feature overlap — some feature combinations are similar across different groups, or the model fails to detect subtle but important patterns in atypical diabetes cases.

This suggests we might need to add new features (like genetic data, lifestyle information, or other key biochemical markers) or adjust the model's penalties to better capture these subtle patterns.

3.4 Model Improvements¶

  1. Initial models:

  • Logistic Regression: Adjusted C to 1.0 and switched to the 'liblinear' solver to strengthen regularisation and speed up convergence.

  • Decision Tree: Increased tree depth (max_depth=6) and reduced minimum samples per leaf (min_samples_leaf=5) to improve model fitting.

  • Random Forest: Increased the number of trees (n_estimators=100) and max depth (max_depth=10) to enhance ensemble performance.

  • LinearSVC: Lowered regularisation strength (C=0.5) and extended maximum iterations (max_iter=20000) for better training stability.

  • KNN: Reduced number of neighbours to 5 to better capture local data structure.

  1. XGBoost model:

  • Improvement focus:

    • As mentioned earlier, recall is the key metric for this project because false negatives (predicting “no diabetes” when the patient actually has diabetes) have serious consequences, potentially delaying treatment.

    • Priority order for optimisation: Recall > F1 Score > Precision。

  • How it’s done:

    • Applied SMOTE oversampling to balance positive and negative samples in the training set.

    • Used RandomizedSearchCV for hyperparameter tuning to boost model performance.

    • Used the best model to predict on the validation set, adjusting classification thresholds as needed to improve recall.。

# 6. XGBoost

# Visualize model classification performance at different thresholds
precisions, recalls, thresholds = precision_recall_curve(y_val, y_val_proba)

# Calculate F1 scores
f1_scores = 2 * (precisions * recalls) / (precisions + recalls + 1e-6)

# Find the threshold that yields the highest F1 score
best_idx = np.argmax(f1_scores)
best_threshold = thresholds[best_idx]
best_f1 = f1_scores[best_idx]

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
plt.plot(thresholds, precisions[:-1], label="Precision", linestyle='--')
plt.plot(thresholds, recalls[:-1], label="Recall", linestyle='-.')
plt.plot(thresholds, f1_scores[:-1], label="F1 Score", linewidth=2)

# Mark the point with the best F1 score
plt.axvline(x=best_threshold, color='red', linestyle=':')
plt.scatter(best_threshold, best_f1, color='red', label=f"Best F1 = {best_f1:.3f} at Threshold = {best_threshold:.2f}")

plt.xlabel("Threshold")
plt.ylabel("Score")
plt.title("Precision, Recall and F1 vs Threshold")
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

The chart shows how the model's precision, recall, and F1 score change at different threshold values.

  • If the main goal is to optimise the F1 score, the best threshold is around 0.65, where the F1 score reaches its highest point at 0.80, indicating a good balance between precision and recall.

  • If prioritising recall (to reduce the risk of missed diagnoses, suitable for large-scale screening), a threshold near 0.40 can be chosen, where recall is close to 0.80, effectively lowering the false negative rate.

  • If precision is the priority, a threshold above 0.65 can be selected, but recall will drop significantly, which may lead to some patients being missed.

from sklearn.model_selection import RandomizedSearchCV
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report, confusion_matrix, roc_auc_score, precision_recall_curve
from scipy.stats import uniform, randint

# Oversample minority class
smote = SMOTE(random_state=42)
X_train_resampled, y_train_resampled = smote.fit_resample(X_train, y_train)

# Hyperparameter distribution for tuning
param_dist = {
    'n_estimators': randint(0, 400),
    'max_depth': randint(3, 6),
    'learning_rate': uniform(0.03, 0.05),
    'subsample': uniform(0.85, 0.15),
    'colsample_bytree': uniform(0.85, 0.15),
    'min_child_weight': randint(1, 4),
    'gamma': uniform(0, 1.5)
}

# Set up randomized hyperparameter search
search = RandomizedSearchCV(
    xgb,
    param_distributions=param_dist,
    n_iter=100,
    scoring='f1',
    cv=5,
    verbose=1,
    n_jobs=-1,
    random_state=42
)

# Fit the search on the oversampled training data
search.fit(X_train_resampled, y_train_resampled)

# Get the best estimator found during search
best_model = search.best_estimator_
y_val_proba = best_model.predict_proba(X_val)[:, 1]

# Define a custom threshold for classifying positive cases
threshold = 0.41
y_val_pred_thresh = (y_val_proba >= threshold).astype(int)

# Function to evaluate model performance given a threshold
def evaluate_model(name, model, X_train, y_train, X_val, y_val, threshold=0.5):
    y_train_proba = model.predict_proba(X_train)[:, 1]
    y_val_proba = model.predict_proba(X_val)[:, 1]

    y_train_pred = (y_train_proba >= threshold).astype(int)
    y_val_pred = (y_val_proba >= threshold).astype(int)

    print(f"{name} Performance (Threshold = {threshold}):")
    print(f"  Train F1: {f1_score(y_train, y_train_pred):.3f}")
    print(f"  Val F1: {f1_score(y_val, y_val_pred):.3f}")
    print(f"  Train Precision: {precision_score(y_train, y_train_pred):.3f}")
    print(f"  Val Precision: {precision_score(y_val, y_val_pred):.3f}")
    print(f"  Train Recall: {recall_score(y_train, y_train_pred):.3f}")
    print(f"  Val Recall: {recall_score(y_val, y_val_pred):.3f}")
    print(f"  Val ROC-AUC: {roc_auc_score(y_val, y_val_proba):.6f}")

# Evaluate the tuned XGBoost model
evaluate_model("XGBoost Tuned", best_model, X_train, y_train, X_val, y_val, threshold=0.41)

Task 4: Reflection¶

4.1 Interpretation of Results:¶

  • The binary classification model for diabetes prediction developed in this project performs well on the test set. The final model (tuned XGBoost) achieved an F1 score of 0.776 and a ROC-AUC of 0.979, indicating strong discriminative power and good generalization performance.

  • The model demonstrated high accuracy and recall on the validation set. In particular, the strong recall performance helps reduce the risk of missed diagnoses. For a chronic disease like diabetes that requires early intervention, minimizing false negatives is crucial. It can help prevent the disease from progressing to more severe stages, providing patients with critical treatment opportunities and potentially reducing long-term healthcare costs and complications.

  • Although a slight trade-off in precision was made to improve recall, a precision of 77.6% still means that nearly 4 out of 5 individuals predicted to have diabetes are correctly identified. In an early screening context, false positives can typically be resolved through follow-up diagnostic testing, without placing undue strain on medical resources or causing excessive anxiety for patients.

4.2 Why the Model Predicts¶

  • The model identified HbA1c levels and blood glucose levels as the most influential features—consistent with well-established medical understanding that elevated blood sugar is a key indicator of diabetes risk.

  • The model's decision logic primarily relies on recognizing combinations of key physiological indicators and health conditions. For example, an individual with advanced age, high BMI, and elevated HbA1c and glucose levels is more likely to be classified as diabetic, regardless of other variables. However, as revealed through error analysis, the model struggles with atypical or borderline cases—individuals whose indicators fall into diagnostic gray zones. These challenges emphasize that while machine learning models can be powerful, clinical expertise remains essential for interpreting predictions, particularly in ambiguous or edge cases.

4.3 Fairness and Ethical Considerations¶

  • Positive Impacts:

    • Early detection can lead to timely interventions for high-risk individuals, reducing disease burden and unnecessary resource use.

    • Risk predictions can inform public health strategies and help optimize the allocation of medical resources.

  • Potential Risks:

    • False positives may cause unnecessary anxiety or lead to unneeded tests and costs. False negatives may delay diagnosis and treatment, increasing the likelihood of serious complications.

    • Even with anonymized data, there are privacy risks; robust data protection and regulatory compliance are critical.

    • If training data lacks demographic diversity, the model may underperform for underrepresented groups, leading to inequitable healthcare outcomes.

    • Any real-world deployment must be guided by clinical judgment, with regular audits to monitor fairness and bias, ensuring the model remains safe, transparent, and equitable across populations.

4.4 Model Interpretability¶

XGBoost is a powerful black-box model whose internal decision-making process is not inherently transparent to humans. However, in the healthcare domain, predictive accuracy alone is not sufficient—both clinicians and patients need to understand why the model makes a particular prediction.

  • To build trust and use the model as a reliable decision support tool, doctors need to understand the reasoning behind predictions. This enables them to validate and integrate model outputs into clinical workflows more responsibly.

  • An interpretable model allows physicians to communicate risk factors and prediction rationale more clearly, helping patients understand their diabetes risk and engage in shared decision-making regarding prevention or treatment.

Improving interpretability can thus enhance model adoption, trust, and ethical transparency in real-world healthcare settings.

4.5 Limitations and Future Work¶

  • Data Limitations:

    • The current dataset lacks comprehensive features such as genetic predispositions, physical activity, diet, and lifestyle habits — all of which play important roles in diabetes risk.

    • Diabetes is influenced by socioeconomic and environmental factors that are not captured here. This may introduce biases or reduce model fairness.

    • Future work should use diverse, representative datasets, and evaluate model performance across subgroups to ensure fairness and inclusiveness.

  • Model Limitations:

    • Despite the use of oversampling techniques like SMOTE, class imbalance remains a challenge. Future work could explore more advanced data balancing methods to mitigate this issue further.

    • The current model performs static, point-in-time predictions and does not account for changes in a patient's health status over time. Future models could incorporate time-series data, enabling the prediction of disease progression evolution over time.

  • Application Limitations:

    • This project is based on a public dataset and has not been validated in real-world clinical settings.
    • For the model to be clinically useful, it must undergo external validation, be compared against expert medical judgment, and be assessed for reliability, safety, and utility in operational healthcare environments.
